.2}], "full_text": "Lecture\nNeuroradiology\nRadiology\n3\nImaging Modalities\n1. Conventional Radiography: Plain x-ray\n2. Computed Tomography: MDCT\n3. Magnetic Resonance Imaging: fMR, MRS\nComputed Tomography\n❖ Computed tomography (CT) works by using\nX-rays from multiple angles to create cross-\nsectional images of the body.\n❖ A CT scanner takes numerous X-ray\nmeasurements as it rotates around the patient,\nand a computer uses this data to reconstruct\ndetailed 2D slices and 3D models of the\nbody's internal structures.\n❖ The core principles rely on the attenuation of\nX-rays based on tissue density and the\nreconstruction of images from multiple projections.\nCT Tissue Characterization\nTissue Contrast depends on Attenuation\nNumber (Hounsfield Unit)\no Air = -1000 HU\no Fat = -50 HU\no Water = 0 HU\no\no Soft Tissue = 25-35 HU\no Acute Hemorrhage = 70-100 HU\no Calcification = 200-300 HU\no Cortical Bone >= 1000 HU Digital Image\nwhich is turned\nafter wards to\nreal image\n31"}